review_blob: Bottle. Champagne-like fizz and aromas. Sticky lacing and big head. Pleasant tart acids and grapefruit-like bitterness. Not quite as sharp as some others. Also distracting iron-like metallic taste at the finish. Would definitely drink again, but not my favorite.

Bottle. Luxurious big-bubbled tan head and oil-black body. Not heavily carbonated. Deep coffee aromas and flavors. While coffee predominates, there is a lot of malt complexity here - more than most imperial stouts without much alcohol pushing through. A dry, flavorful, satisfying beer.
Bottle. This is a great beer. Sharp, tart, and flavorful. Very sour. Among the better sour red/brown beers around. No complaints.

Bottle. Really rich, flavorful beer. Tremendous depth to the malt with dark fruit, toffee, bready flavors. Combines attributes of a great German beer with a great Belgian Abbey beer. Not too heavy, though. Dont even taste the alcohol. Very impressive.
Draft taster. Lemon lime aroma. Cloudy yellow appearance with good lacing and medium carbonation. Light Berliner Weiss style sour. Tart lime, mineral white wine flavors. Pretty good, a bit thin.
Draft taster. Aroma is vinegar. Dark cloudy reddish brown color. Great Flanders red brown sour with the dark vinegar sour start and sweet finish. Impressive.
Draft taster. Fruity aroma. Cloudy golden color, no head, good carbonation. Nicely tart, stone fruit peach, plum. Some funk to round it out but well balanced. Delicious.
beer_name: Sudwerk Brewers Cut: Pluot Is Not A Planet

review_blob: 2014 bottle for tasting. Cherries are featured. Equally sour and funky and as a result doesnt have the bite I was hoping for. A bit flat. Tasty but not impressive for the style.

2012 bottle tasting. Not what I was hoping for. Has aroma and flavors of those round candy buttons you have to bite
 off the shiny paper when you were a kid and didnt even know how bad of a candy it is. Theres obviously some white wine stuff going on here but its ruined.
2012 bottle tasting. Really sour with cherry, red wine, dark fruits flavors. Really potent but you just keep wanting another sip. Perfect dark sour.
2013 bottle taste. Dark vinous, chocolate, wood flavors. Tart but primarily funky at this point. Kind of like a dark sour Abbey beer aged in wine barrels. Not my favorite, but not bad.
Bottle. Clean, complex sour focusing on the citrus fruits. Grapefruit, lemon. Quite tart to begin, settling with some rind-y bitterness at the back of the palate.
On draft at the brewery. Nice raspberry sour, thick cloudy appearance like grapefruit juice. Moderately sour, sticky sugars. Fine beer.
On draft as part of a Mikkeller flight. Really enjoyed this. Light, perfectly balanced beer, both sweet and sour.
Bottle. Really delicious dark beer with hints of Belgian dubbel/quad (at first) and American porter dryness(at the end) mixed together.
On draft at the brewery. Coffee forward, which seemed too strong for my taste and the style. Otherwise, good looking clear brown ale with nice sweetness. Too bad the coffee overwhelmed it.
On draft at the brewery. Well-balanced saison with some good spice, nice malts, not too much hoppiness. Light, refreshing, but not boring. Was the best beer I tried out of the four on the sampler.

From the bottle. Phenomenal concoction here. Really pretty golden orange color with sticky white fluffy head and perfect carbonation. Unbelievable pure fruit flavors of pineapple and mandarin cut by the wheat and gentle hops. Gently sour with fruity sweet finish without being syrupy or cloying. Dont even taste any alcohol. One of my new favorites!

From bottle. Dark with stout-like tan head, though thin. Very well-balanced sour stout. Complex aromas and flavors, wine-like at times, with coffee/chocolate and various fruit flavors. Pretty sour too, which was nice.
On draft in Arcata, CA. Wonderfully complex sour. Dry mouth feel with apples, wine, stonefruits. Quite sour and well balanced.

From the bottle. Nice quad, though not spectacular. They got the carbonation, warmth, sweetness right, though the color and flavor lack the richness you would really hope for. I did not find this to be very bitter. The flavor profile and mouthfeel approximate a good quad. Nicely done.
beer_name: Boulevard Smokestack Series - The Sixth Glass Quadrupel

beer_brewer_name: Schneider Weisse G. Schneider & Sohn GmbH
review_blob: From small bottle. Rich cloudy mahogany color with small head. Strong intense and dense flavors of dark fruits, wine, and alcohol which crowd out the wheat but not completely. If you like really strong beers, this is very tasty and drinkable.
From the small bottle. Overall an excellent Abbey dubbel, Trappist worthy. Complex, sweet, flavorful. Nice carbonation. A little thin compared to the best of the best, but its a quibble.

From the bottle. Straightforward golden sour balanced with grapefruit/lemon and resiny hop flavors. Moderately sour, mildly bitter. Finishes with a soft sweetness and some more grapefruit bitterness. I was expecting a more hop-forward beer, but very tasty.

Delicious first-class belgian dubbel reproduction, from the fine lively carbonation to the rich color to the smooth and flavorful malts to the sweet candi sugar to the well-hidden booze. Thank you Unibroue!
From small bottle. Wonderful dark fruit aroma with thin lacy head. Complex flavors, strong alcohol content, but incredibly smooth. Sweeter than other dark strong ales with perfect carbonation
beer_name: Gouden Carolus Cuvee Van De Keizer Blauw/Blue

review_blob: Very Happy with this bottle. When cold, the carbonation is strong and balances out the smooth sweetness. Complex aroma and flavors. When warm, you can really enjoy the palate and warm booze. Goes head to head with Trappist dark ales.
On draft at the brewery. Opaque dark brown caramel color with small white head. Toffee aromas and flavors, with butterscotch sweetness. A little cloying for my taste.
On draft at brewery. Pale cloudy yellow color with small white head. Grapefruit pineapple aroma. Lemon peel flavor. Slight bitterness. Minimal spice. Mild yeastiness. OK saison.
On draft at brewery. Honey brown color with white head. Doesnt quite cut it for an Abbey ale. Weak and generic flavors predominate.
Draft at the brewery. Pretty mahogany color with small head and small lacing. Delicious dark fruit malt flavors with smoky edge. Strong but not too strong. Very drinkable.

From bottle. This pushes the boundary between brown ale and porter, given the strong coffee, chocolate, and toasted flavors. Its a bit lighter in the beginning, but the finish is particularly porter-like. Not a bad porter, but a porter nonetheless.
At the brewery. Beautiful medium dark red sour, with some typical sweetness cut by strong acid and berry tones. Complex acidity lingers.
One of the most convincing American dubbels out there. Very well-balanced, hides the alcohol really well with a candi sweetness. Rich dark fruit flavors.

Nearly black pour from draft. Lot of of white lacing. Starts rich and smoky, but could use a little more depth and character. Finish is a bit off, nicely described as kolsch-like, by loses a little of the malty sweetness. Pretty good overall.
beer_name: Sonoma Springs Bruja Majik Verona Alt

review_blob: From a bottle. Wow -- amazing smoked beer with rich mahogany color, some lacing of a thin white head. Smoky without being overly burnt or roasted. Sweet, smooth malty goodness. The epitome of a smoked beer.
Bottle. A delicious effervescent, grassy, malt-heavy, smooth, and sweet kolsch. Light alcohol content makes this a really drinkable, yet flavorful, beer.

Bottle, pretty warm. Beautiful hazy orange with no head or lacing. Delicious tart strawberry beer, well-balanced with some sweetness as the end. Could be a little more intensely tart and less syrupy sweet in the middle, but quite a special concoction.
From bottle. Could be more crisply sour if not for the somewhat cloying sweetness underlying the palate. Prominent dark grapes.
beer_name: The Rare Barrel Shadows of Their Eyes

review_blob: Draft. Very delicious cabernet-colored beer. Quite tart, perfectly seasoned with herbs, almost a sour.

From the can. Rich reddish/purple color with thin off-white head and minimal lacing. Moderately carbonated. Complex aroma and palate, nicely resembling a classic abbey strong dark ale, with the requisite sweetness and dark fruit flavors. Hides the alcohol well until the very end and it adds a nice bite to balance the sugar. Very delicious.

Bottle. Beautiful looking beer, not particularly aromatic. Rich malts, but not too sweet due to a balanced hop presence. Less intense than the Samuel Smith, for instance. Dont taste any alcohol. Very drinkable.
beer_name: AleSmith Nut Brown English-Style Ale (Bottle and Draft)

review_blob: Can. Rich brown mahogany color, beige head. Not too aromatic. Complex maltiness, but overpowered by alcohol in my opinion.
Draft. Clear golden with frothy white head. Medium bodied, sweet malts up front with a crisp and well balanced hop middle. Finishes slightly sweet and crisp. Tasty and drinkable.

From growler. Nice golden color, minimal white head without much lacing. Light carbonation. Very complex palate without dominant flavors, good acid, but also with the brewerys typical sticky sweetness to balance it out. Hints of oak and vanilla come through. One of the better blends Ive had there.

On draft. Aroma is golden sour, slightly hazy golden color, light fizz and minimal lacing. Sticky mouth feel, sweet taste with strong hints of berry and acid. Delicious and well balanced. Raspberry finish.

Bottle. Deep walnut color, small white head, minimal lacing. Aromas of grassy malts. Taste is sweet to start, turning slightly bitter the longer you hold it on your tongue. Creamy, medium-full bodied mouthfeel, pretty satisfying. Its that moment when the sweet turns bitter that feels unique.
Bottle. Interesting but not particularly satisfying balance of sweet malts and hoppy bitternerss. Unfortunately, the two combine to make for a blandish beer.

On draft, likely a relatively new beer. Smokey malt aroma. Beautiful amber color with small white head, good lacing. Delicious malty, lightly smoked treat. A nice example of what really good minimally-hopped beer can taste like. Flavorful, sweet. Not trying to be too fancy.

On nitro. Pretty pitch black with creamy tan head. Mild roasted malt aromas. Really smooth, medium bodied, straightforward porter. Not too smoky or roasted, lets you appreciate the dark malts. Great clean beer.
